THE LATINITY OF THE OLD LATIN BIBLE 97

V. litus; Gk. χεῖλος ; cf. Loc. 7:32: Haec autem translatio ubi labium maris posuit pro litore, assidua est in Scripturas, sed rara estin latinis codicibus, etc.

latitudo, V. nervus; Gk. πλάτος; 32:253 latitudo semoris means the broad part of the thigh.

legitima, V. leges; Gk. νόμιμα; precepts, statutes; 26: 5; very rare 3 cf. Nep. Phoc. 42; also found in Vulg.

lenis, V. ibid.; Gk. λεῖος; smooth, free from hair, in contrast to pilosus, 27:11; cf. Hildeb. ad Apul. 5:21: I rt antiquis editis libris lenis et levis inter se confusa sunt.

liber, V. 2:4 omits3 5:13 ibid.; Gk. βίβλος ; liber creaturae, 2:4=the ac- count of creation3 liber nativitatis, 5:1=genealogical account, a family tree.

lignum, V. ibid.; Gk. ξύλοις 1:11, 12, 29; 229, 16, 17; 321, 2, 6, 11, 17, 22, 24, tree; Eccles. Lat.; in 3:8 it means grove. The word arbor occurs in De Gen. con. Man. 3:23, 11; also in 1814, where the LXX has δένδρον; and in 22: 13.

luminare, V. ibid.; Gk. φωστήρ; a heavenly body, a luminary3 1:14, 15. Eccles. Lat. Cf. Ronsch, p. 48.

maledicere, V. ibid.; Gk. καταρᾶν; to curse; 8:213 12: 3; 27:293 a mean- ing peculiar to Eccles. Lat. Used trans. with the Ace. The P.P. maledictus is used as an adjective. Gk. ἐπικατάρατος; 3:14; 4:11; 9:25; 27:29.

manducare, V. comedere; Gk. ἐσθίειν, except 43: 3, where συνέσθειν; to eat3 2:173 3t5, 11, 133 18:53 27:73 40:19, etc., edere also occurs; cf. 2:173 322, 3, 11, 12, etc. For use of manducare see Petron. 563 Varro R.R. 317, 9.

magnificare, ci. p. 117. In the clause magnificata est pars, etc., 43:34, magnificata is either to be considered as an Adj., or facta est has the same force as est alone. The LXX has the Aor. Pass. oi the verb, ἐμεγαλύνθη.

manuS, V. potestas; Gk. χεῖρ; 41:35; cf. Loc. 1:161 where Aug. explains the phrase sub manu as equivalent to sub potestate. A legal expression.

mare, V. occidens; Gk. θάλασσα; the west3 28:14; 13:14, etc. Evident- ly a local idiom; comes into the Lat. though the LXX from the Hebrew.

mittere, V. inicere; Gk. ἐπιβάλλειν; 39:73 mittere oculos, cf. Loc. 1:1433 solet et apud vos vulgo esse usitata locutio pro eo quod est, amavit eum.
